\par }\pard \fi567\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright {\i\lang1033\cgrid0 Appendix A.
\par Name:}{\lang1033\cgrid0  Le Chiffre.
\par }{\i\lang1033\cgrid0 Aliases:}{\lang1033\cgrid0  Variations on the words 'cypher' or 'number' in different languages; eg 'Herr Ziffer'. 
\par }{\i\lang1033\cgrid0 Origin:}{\lang1033\cgrid0  Unknown.
\par First encountered as a displaced person, inmate of Dachau DP camp in the US Zone of Germany, June 1945. Apparently suffering from amnesia and paralysis of vocal chords (? both feigned). Dumbness succumbed to therapy, b
ut subject continued to claim total loss of memory except associations with Alsace\_Lorraine and Strasbourg whither he was transferred in September 1945, on Stateless Passport No 304\_
596. Adopted the name 'Le Chiffre' ('since I am only a number on a passport'). No Christian names.
\par }{\i\lang1033\cgrid0 Age:}{\lang1033\cgrid0  About 45.
\par Description: Height 5 ft 8 ins. Weight 18 stones. Complexion very pale. Clean\_shaven. Hair red\_brown, 'en brosse'. Eyes very dark brown with whites showing all round iris. Small, rather feminine mouth. False teeth of
 expensive quality. Ears small, with large lobes, indicating some Jewish blood. Hands small, well\_
tended, hirsute. Feet small. Racially, subject is probably a mixture of Mediterranean with Prussian or Polish strains. Dresses well and meticulously, generally in dark double\_
breasted suits. Smokes incessantly Caporals, using a denicotinizing holder. At frequent intervals inhales from benzedrine inhaler. Voice soft and even. Bilingual in French and English. Good German. Traces of Marseilles accent. Smiles infre
quently. Does not laugh.
\par }{\i\lang1033\cgrid0 Habits:}{\lang1033\cgrid0 
 Mostly expensive, but discreet. Large sexual appetites. Flagellant. Expert driver of fast cars. Adept with small arms and other forms of personal combat, including knives. Carries three Eversharp razor blades, in hat\_band, 
heel of left shoe and cigarette\_case. Knowledge of accountancy and mathematics. Fine gambler. Always accompanied by two armed guards, well\_dressed, one French, one German (details available).
\par }{\i\lang1033\cgrid0 Comment:}{\lang1033\cgrid0  A formidable and dangerous agent of the USSR, controlled by Leningrad Section III through Paris.
\par }\pard \qr\fi567\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright {\i\lang1033\cgrid0 Signed: Archivist.
\par }\pard \fi567\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright {\i\lang1033\cgrid0 Appendix B.
\par Subject:}{\lang1033\cgrid0  SMERSH
\par }{\i\lang1033\cgrid0 Sources:}{\lang1033\cgrid0  Own archives and scanty material made available by Deuxi\'e8me Bureau and CIA Washington.
\par SMERSH is a conjunction of two Russian words: 'Smyert Shpionam', meaning roughly: 'Death to Spies'.
\par Ranks above MWD (formerly NKVD) and is believed to come under the personal direction of Beria.
\par Headquarters: Leningrad (sub\_station at Moscow).
\par Its tasks is the elimination of all forms of treachery and back\_sliding with the va
rious branches of the Soviet Secret Service and Secret Police at home and abroad. It is the most powerful and feared organization in the USSR and is popularly believed never to have failed in a mission of vengeance.
\par It is thought that SMERSH was responsible for the assassination of Trotsky in Mexico (22 August 1940) and may indeed have made its name with this successful murder after attempts by other Russian individuals and organizations had failed.
\par SMERSH was next heard of when Hitler attacked Russia. It w
as then rapidly expanded to cope with treachery and double agents during the retreat of the Soviet forces in 1941. At that time it worked as an execution squad for the NKVD and its present selective mission was not so clearly defined.
\par The organization itself was thoroughly purged after the war and is now believed to consist of only a few hundred operatives of very high quality divided into five sections:
\par Department I: In charge of counter\_intelligence among Soviet organizations at home and abroad.
\par Department II: Operations, including executions.
\par Department III: Administration and Finance.
\par Department IV: Investigations and legal work. Personnel.
\par Department V: Prosecutions: the section which passes final judgement on all victims.
\par Only one SMERSH operative has come into our hands since the war: Goytchev, alias Garrad\_Jones. He shot Petchora, medical officer at the Yugoslav Embassy, in Hyde Park, 7 August 1948. During interrogation he committed suicide by swallowing a coat\_
button of compressed potassium cyanide. He revealed nothing beyond his membership of SMERSH, of which he was arrogantly boastful.
\par We believe that the following British double agents were victims of SMERSH: Donovan, Harthrop\_Vane, Elizabeth Dumont, Ventnor, Mace, Savarin. (For details see Morgue: Section Q.)
\par }{\i\lang1033\cgrid0 Conclusion:}{\lang1033\cgrid0  Every effort should be made to improve our knowledge of this very powerful organization and destroy its operatives.
\par 
