\par }\pard\plain \fi567\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \lang2057\cgrid {\lang1033\cgrid0 Head of S (the section of the Secret Service concerned with 
the Soviet Union) was so keen on his plan for the destruction of Le Chiffre, and it was basically his own plan, that he took the memorandum himself and went up to the top floor of the gloomy building overlooking Regent's Park and through the green baize d
oor and along the corridor to the end room.
\par He walked belligerently up to M's Chief of Staff, a young sapper who had earned his spurs as one of the secretariat to the Chiefs of Staff committee after having been wounded during a sabotage operation in 1944, a
nd had kept his sense of humour in spite of both experiences.
\par 'Now look here, Bill. I want to sell something to the Chief. Is this a good moment?'
\par 'What do you think, Penny?' The Chief of Staff turned to M's private secretary who shared the room with him.
\par Miss Moneypenny would have been desirable but for eyes which were cool and direct and quizzical.
\par 'Should be all right. He won a bit of a victory at the FO this morning and he's not got anyone for the next half an hour.' She smiled encouragingly at Head of S whom she liked for himself and for the importance of his section.
\par 'Well, here's the dope, Bill.' He handed over the black folder with the red star which stood for Top Secret. 'And for God's sake look enthusiastic when you give it him. And tell him I'll wait here and read a good code\_
book while he's considering it. He may want some more details, and anyway I want to see you two don't pester him with anything else until he's finished.'
\par 'All right, sir.' The Chief of Staff pressed a switch leant towards the intercom on his desk.
\par 'Yes?' asked a quiet, flat voice.
\par 'Head of S has an urgent docket for you, sir.'
\par There was a pause.
\par 'Bring it in,' said a voice.
\par The Chief of Staff released the switch and stood up.
\par 'Thanks, Bill. I'll be next door,' said Head of S.
\par The Chief of Staff crossed his office and went through the double doors leading into M's room. In a moment he came out and over the entrance a small blue light burned the warning that M was not to be disturbed.
