\par James Bond's interview with M had been short.
\par 'What about it, Bond?' asked M when Bond came back into his room after reading Head of S's memorandum and after gazing for ten minutes out of the waiting\_room window at the distant trees in the park.
\par Bond looked across the desk into the shrewd, clear eyes.
\par 'It's very kind of you, sir, I'd like to do it. But I can't promise to win. The odds at baccarat are the best after }{\i\lang1033\cgrid0 trente\_et\_quarante}{\lang1033\cgrid0  \emdash  evens except for the tiny }{\i\lang1033\cgrid0 cagnotte}{
\lang1033\cgrid0  \emdash  but I might get a bad run against me and get cleaned out. Play's going to he pretty high \emdash  opening'll go up to half a million, I should think.'
\par Bond was stopped by the cold eyes. M knew all this already, knew the odds at baccarat as well as Bond. That was his job \emdash  knowing the odds at everything, and knowing men, his own and the opposition's. Bond wished he ha
d kept quiet about his misgivings.
\par 'He can have a bad run too,' said M. 'You'll have plenty of capital. Up to twenty\_five million, the same as him. We'll start you on ten and send you another ten when you've had a look round. You can make the extra five yo
urself.' He smiled. 'Go over a few days before the big game starts and get your hand in. Have a talk to Q about rooms and trains, and any equipment you want. The Paymaster will fix the funds. I'm going to ask the Deuxi\'e8
me to stand by. It's their territory 
and as it is we shall be lucky if they don't kick up rough. I'll try and persuade them to send Mathis. You seemed to get on well with him in Monte Carlo on that other Casino job. And I'm going to tell Washington because of the NATO angle. CIA have got one
 or two good men at Fontainebleau with the joint intelligence chaps there. Anything else?'
\par Bond shook his head. 'I'd certainly like to have Mathis, sir.'
\par 'Well, we'll see. Try and bring it off. We're going to look pretty foolish if you don't. And watch out. This sounds an amusing job, but I don't think it's going to be. Le Chiffre is a good man. Well, best of luck.'
\par 'Thank you, sir,' said Bond and went to the door.
\par 'Just a minute.'
\par Bond turned.
\par I think I'll keep you covered, Bond. Two heads are better than one and you'll need someone to run your communications. I'll think it over. They'll get in touch with you at Royale. You needn't worry. It'll be someone good.'
\par Bond would have preferred to work alone, but one didn't argue with M. He left the room hoping that the man they sent would be loyal to him and neither stupid, nor, worse still, ambitious.
